    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-07-21T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-07-21T23:00:00-05:00" n="73"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d73">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/808: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-22T11:00:00+07:00"
                            >July 22, 1940—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 2 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>356. Department’s 124, July 20, 4 p.m. I do not feel that Generalissimo expects
                    any replies to statements made to me and reported in my 338, July 12, 9 a.m. The
                    Secretary’s statements in regard to closing of Indochina and Burma
                        frontiers<note n="96" xml:id="d73fn96">See press release of July 16, <ref
                            target="frus1931-41v02#pg_101">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 101</ref>, and Department’s telegram
                        No. 275, July 17, 7 p.m., <ref target="#pg_52">p. 52</ref>.</note> reported
                    in radio bulletins numbers 168 and 169 received wide publicity here and were
                    favorably commented upon. They indicate as nothing else we might say just where
                    we stand. I therefore respectfully suggest that unless Department feels that it
                    is very important it make to the Generalissimo the statements set down in the
                    Department’s instruction under reference, the matter of the Department’s
                    suggestions to me be permitted to stand uncommented upon.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
